{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504413"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2328"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2328"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.07,0.19,0.5,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49594"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2328"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34865"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1932"},{"type":"tags","id":"6039"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47401"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49594"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department complaining of a 12-hour history of lower back pain, worse when straightening her back. This pain came on suddenly on lifting a heavy potted plant whilst gardening. This pain does not radiate towards her neck or legs. She does not have any bowel or bladder symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination, she appears comfortable. Her pulse rate is 86/min, blood pressure 136/90 mmHg, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. There is focal tenderness on deep palpation of her lower spinous process, in particular at the level of T12. There are no lower limb motor or sensory deficits. The rest of her examination is unremarkable. A lower back X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete bed rest and immobilisation for six weeks","Elective vertebral fusion surgery","Initiate bisphosphonate therapy","Simple analgesia and mobilisation as tolerated","Spinal brace for 8 - 12 weeks"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an older patient who presents with focal pain in her lower back from a sudden onset of lifting a heavy item. This is indicative of mechanical trauma, such as a vertebral compression fracture. Typically, compression fractures are fragility fractures common in patients with a background of osteoporosis - a common condition associated with the older population. This occurs when bone cortices are thinned and/or cancellous bone has decreased trabecular continuity. Minimal trauma would result in a compression or wedge fracture between each vertebral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows an osteoporotic vertebral crush fracture of T12. The majority of such patients can be treated with observation and adequate \u003Cstrong\u003Esimple analgesia with the gradual return of activity/mobilisation as tolerated\u003C/strong\u003E. Physical activity should be resumed as quickly as possible if tolerated. This is useful for gait and core strengthening when the patient can tolerate the level of activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete bed rest and immobilisation\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as inactivity may result in further bone loss and reconditioning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndications for and timing of surgical management (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebral fusion surgery\u003C/strong\u003E) remains controversial. There is a limited beneficial effect in vertebral augmentation, and most patients can be treated successfully with conservative management. Surgical management may benefit specific patient groups - debilitating pain and in those who are not improving with conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal brace\u003C/strong\u003E may be incorporated in the management of pain relief in patients with osteoporotic compression fractures. However, it should only be used in the acute phase of treatment. Long-term use of a spinal brace may result in atrophy of the core musculature and may result in future risk of falls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELong term management should include pharmacotherapy to improve the low bone mineral density such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ebisphosphonates\u003C/strong\u003E, denosumab, raloxifene or teriparatide. This may lead to increased bone mass and a reduction in the rate of new fractures. However, the most appropriate first step in management is adequate pain relief and mobilisation as soon as possible. In this case, where there is obvious osteoporosis, a spinal brace could also be considered. Once the pain issues have been addressed, then a bisphosphonate could be prescribed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pain relief and early mobilisation should be the initial plan of management for a vertebral crush fracture."],"references":["Lee HM, Park SY, Lee SH, et al. Comparative analysis of clinical outcomes in patients with osteoporotic vertebral compression fractures (OVCFs): conservative treatment versus balloon kyphoplasty. Spine J. 2012;12:998. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1529943012005864","Agulnek AN, O\u0027Leary KJ, Edwards BJ. Acute vertebral fracture. J Hosp Med 2009;4:E20. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19507248/","Ebeling PR, Akesson K, Bauer DC, et al. The Efficacy and Safety of Vertebral Augmentation: A Second ASBMR Task Force Report. J Bone Miner Res. 2019;34:3. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30677181/","Kim HJ, Yi JM, Cho HG, et al. Comparative study of the treatment outcomes of osteoporotic compression fractures without neurologic injury using a rigid brace, a soft brace, and no brace: a prospective randomized controlled non-inferiority trial. J Bone Joint Surg Am. 2014;96:1959. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25471910/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34865"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2328"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16861"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16861"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/34be6918-d8e6-4c06-beb0-78029a197a69.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/34be6918-d8e6-4c06-beb0-78029a197a69.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":252,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34865"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-01T08:57:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-01T09:00:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2328"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49594"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"t